> By contrast, the Harvard-architecture (which I think predates the
> Von Neuman architecture) uses separate "program" and "memory"
> spaces.  If those spaces are rigidly separated then programs
> can not modify themselves or each other, preventing (I think)
> the propagation of viruses.  Many common microcontrollers use
> this type of architecture, with program memory in prom and
> data memory in ram.

